**Category:** essay-draft speech-acts narrative-theory searle perlocutionary-effects exposure dramatic-space

**Abstract:**
Essay dated August 21, 1992 titled "Speech-acts and Narrative Theories" comparing speech-act theory (ordinary language practices of exposed agents) with narrative theory (literary genres dealing with texts). Argues speech-act theory projects its analytic character onto the analysand, ignoring the dramatic sequence captured by narratives. Critiques Searle's distinction between illocutionary and perlocutionary effects. Distinguishes levels: life, texts, and theory of texts.

**AI Recommendation:** Early essay developing speech-act critique; precedes 96-SEP series.

